article.description:
With Tracy McGrady and Mike Miller hurting, Monty
Williams and Troy Hudson stepped up for the Orlando Magic.
article.headline: Win over Heat would give Magic No. 4 spot
article.linkText: Magic halt three-game slide, target East's No. 4 spot
article.story:
ATLANTA (AP) -- With Tracy McGrady and Mike Miller hurting, Monty Williams and Troy Hudson stepped up for the Orlando Magic.
Williams

"A lot of guys got some rest," Williams said. "We've been losing games like this." Williams scored a season-high 23 points and Hudson added 18 as the Magic snapped a three-game losing streak by beating the Atlanta Hawks 102-95 Tuesday night. A victory over Miami on Wednesday in Orlando would give the Magic the fourth spot in the Eastern Conference playoffs and homecourt advantage in the best-of-five opening series against the No. 5 seed. McGrady, who finished with 16 points, showed no visible discomfort after seeing a back specialist in Atlanta earlier Tuesday. An MVP candidate and the NBA's fourth-leading scorer, McGrady shot 6-for-17 and handed out seven assists. His back started to stiffen as the game wore on, and McGrady said it began to ache when he jumped and landed. Magic coach Doc Rivers indicated he might make McGrady rest against Miami. "It'll be up to me, but the way I was running the last few minutes of the game -- I don't want to feel like that," McGrady said. "Health is more important than homecourt. Plus, I still believe in my guys to get the job done." Rivers likely won't make a decision until game time. Miller, Orlando's second-leading scorer, returned to the injured list Tuesday with a sprained left ankle. "We're just trying to survive the regular season. Every night it looks like somebody else is dropping," Rivers said. "Tomorrow is important, but it's more important for us to get out of that game healthy." The game was stopped briefly with 9:04 remaining as Jason Terry and Don Reid were ejected for fighting. Orlando was leading 81-69 when Terry took the ball at the top of the Atlanta key and head-faked past Troy Hudson. Driving the lane, Terry was slammed to the floor as Reid corralled him with his right arm. After landing on his back, Terry arose and pushed Reid from behind. Reid tried to retaliate before being restrained by teammates. "If I wanted to play for the Falcons, I would have signed up for it," Terry said. "He could have grabbed me and made sure I didn't fall. It is what it is." When told that Reid claimed he only touched the ball, Terry said, "That's O.K. I got all head when I retaliated. Our guys played really hard, but we couldn't get the win. It was a dirty play all the way around. For me, whenever I see him again, it's going to be personal." The Hawks, who've lost four of six overall and 13 of 18 to the Magic, closed to 88-86 on Jacque Vaughn's layup. But Atlanta didn't threaten again after Pat Garrity's straightaway 3-pointer made it 94-86 with 2:42 remaining. "That was a big basket for Pat and the team," Hudson said. "We were hitting off our screens and as the game wore on, we were getting more and more guys open." Williams, who shot 11-for-16, hadn't scored this many points since April 8, 1997, when he played for San Antonio and had a career-high 30 against Denver. Terry, coming off Saturday's 43-point effort in a double-overtime win over Cleveland, finished with 12 points on 5-for-13 shooting. Shareef Abdur-Rahim led Atlanta with 23 points and 11 rebounds. Hudson scored 18 points for the Magic, who had won five of six before beginning a three-game losing streak. Game notes
Orlando activated Jud Buechler from the injured list before the game. ... Hudson replaced Miller, making his third start of the season. ... Backup center Patrick Ewing, who did not play Saturday, entered in the first quarter and finished with 12 points in 16 minutes. "I have one more year on my contract, and at the end of the season we'll sit down and contemplate what I want to do," Ewing said when asked if he plans to retire. "Right now, I'm not even thinking about it." ... The Magic led 50-48 despite getting outrebounded 32-18 in the first half. ... Ending with a 54-37 advantage overall, Atlanta became the fourth straight team to beat Orlando on the boards.
